This is Daryl Lane and David Crews.

06:37.120 --> 06:40.040
In 1973, Brian Aldiss published a book

06:40.040 --> 06:41.740
on the origin and history of science fiction

06:41.740 --> 06:43.240
entitled Billion Year Spree.

06:43.240 --> 06:46.160
He gave us an interesting account of the reasons he wrote the book

06:46.160 --> 06:48.320
including some comments on one of his novels,

06:48.320 --> 06:49.460
Barefoot in the Head.

06:50.060 --> 07:02.340
Well, I'd written a novel called Barefoot in the Head, and it really didn't receive a very kind initial attention although the premise was simple enough.

07:03.600 --> 07:08.800
Barefoot in the Head was about the world stopped in its tracks by drugs.

07:08.800 --> 07:10.640
This was the late 60s, remember?

07:11.840 --> 07:19.760
When the flower power people had been around and we had had all this love-in stuff

07:20.720 --> 07:27.660
and towards the end of the 60s, the bills, as we say in England

07:27.660 --> 07:31.220
the checks were coming in for all that kind of stuff

07:31.220 --> 07:33.820
and they were already finding the fetuses

07:33.820 --> 07:36.200
in the trash cans of Haight-Ashbury

07:36.200 --> 07:40.920
so that Barefoot in the Head was an ambivalent book written in a difficult language

07:48.440 --> 07:55.900
and I was a little surprised at the tepid response it got,

07:55.900 --> 07:58.860
the angry response it got, the anonymous letters.

07:58.860 --> 08:02.500
So I thought, well, let's be finished with the science fiction field,

08:03.680 --> 08:12.960
and I thought, well, before I leave it, I ought to write down all that I know and love about it before I forget,

08:13.940 --> 08:24.640
and so really I settled down with that in mind to write Billion Year Spree and also to have an argument as I raised my hat and left the science fictional community,

08:26.220 --> 08:36.900
but by the time I got to the end of the thing, you know, three years had passed and just writing the book turned me on to science fiction again.

08:37.720 --> 08:41.120
Billion Year Spree is full of Aldiss' personal but fascinating ideas.

08:41.120 --> 08:49.680
One provocative idea, heresy to some science fiction fans, was that Hugo Gernsback, the father of modern science fiction, was a disastrous influence on the field

08:49.680 --> 08:51.780
We asked Aldiss what he meant by that.

08:51.780 --> 09:06.980
Well, as you probably know that I did say something of that sort and since then people have been threatening to break my legs and my arms and shoot me and hang me, and kick me out of the science fiction field and all sorts of things like that,

09:07.700 --> 09:23.420
but I guess that what I was worried about was the way science fiction was segregated by Gernsback into a magazine,

09:23.420 --> 09:36.880
so that if you wanted to find science fiction you had to go to a magazine that had a name like Astounding or Amazing or Staggering

09:36.880 --> 09:47.600
which had a huge three-dimensional title with rivets in it that resulted in a monoculture,

09:47.600 --> 09:54.300
and we all know that there are dangers in monoculture and,

09:54.300 --> 10:04.560
I simply thought that science fiction would be better as an uncaged animal that could rove at large where it would,

10:04.560 --> 10:14.940
but nowadays people complain that science fiction is segregated and that people think you're funny if you read it,

10:14.940 --> 10:23.360
and that it has to have a special place in a bookshop right next to weirdo cult books about flying saucers or whatever.

10:23.360 --> 10:27.780
Well my answer to that is that yes I agree.

10:27.780 --> 10:29.260
I think that's too bad.

10:29.260 --> 10:40.880
I think science fiction is much better than that but the reason why it is there is because of the segregation that was introduced by Hugo Gernsback that was my argument.

10:41.780 --> 10:50.880
Anyone seeking to gain a perspective on science fiction and fantasy should read Billion Year Spree, a personal but fascinating account of the field by one of science fiction's true men of letters.

10:50.880 --> 10:53.060
Tomorrow, more with Brian Aldiss.

