12:33.920 --> 12:38.340
Brian Aldiss does unexpected but fascinating things in his science fiction stories.

12:38.340 --> 12:40.180
Though Aldiss is often an innovator,

12:40.180 --> 12:43.400
He also understands and cherishes the traditions of science fiction.

12:43.400 --> 12:48.780
Aldiss has demonstrated his fondness for science fiction's past by redoing some of its classic novels.

12:48.780 --> 12:53.720
An Island Called Moreau, for instance was based on H.G. Wells' The Island of Dr. Moreau,

12:53.720 --> 12:55.600
And his book Frankenstein Unbound

12:55.600 --> 13:00.700
Drew on Mary Shelley's Frankenstein, published in 1818, which some call the first science fiction novel.

13:00.700 --> 13:05.140
Aldiss relates the impulse behind his writing of Frankenstein Unbound.

13:06.140 --> 13:20.720
I think that I write about the things that fascinate me most, and I'm kind of a literary man and I certainly much admire Mary Shelley's Frankenstein.

13:20.720 --> 13:27.660
It's the most remarkable work for anyone, not least for a young lady not quite touching 18.

13:28.960 --> 13:34.020
And when I had the impulse to write Frankenstein Unbound,

13:34.020 --> 13:45.320
It was really an exegetical impulse to draw everybody's attention if possible to the excellence of that original novel,

13:45.320 --> 13:59.400
Which as you know has been slandered and pilloried by the filmmakers who've seen nothing better in it than a stupid, shambling, and inarticulate monster.

13:59.400 --> 14:17.700
I wanted to restore the monster to his true evil power as an articulate feeling and maimed being worthy of our compassion and perhaps our hatred.

14:19.240 --> 14:25.340
Aldiss says there was a true creative impulse behind Frankenstein Unbound but that wasn't so for An Island called Moreau.

14:26.240 --> 14:38.600
I have to admit that later on I did the same thing with Wells' Island of Dr. Moreau and that was I believe ill-advised

14:38.600 --> 14:55.440
It's one of the few novels I've written that didn't begin with some kind of genuine lust to create will to create with fire in my stomach.

14:56.580 --> 15:03.020
I just thought it was something I could do and that was too tiny a motive I believe for the book that I eventually turned out.

15:03.700 --> 15:11.900
I don't believe that it supersedes or in any way aids the Wells version.

15:11.900 --> 15:20.840
The funny thing is I have to say that that novel was extremely well received in this country and in Great Britain.

15:21.940 --> 15:26.000
Another Aldiss tribute to science fiction's past is his novella The Saliva Tree.

15:26.000 --> 15:31.160
It's a playful book, a clever tribute to H.G. Wells who happens to be an unseen character in it.

15:31.160 --> 15:35.680
It's about an invisible alien monster ravaging the countryside of late Victorian England.

15:35.680 --> 15:44.200
Invading monsters and invisibility are two of Wells' themes of course and during the story all of Wells' themes and the titles of his books are somehow worked in.

15:44.200 --> 15:49.920
The story's main character Gregory Rolles has been writing letters to H.G. Wells about the happenings in the countryside.

15:50.460 --> 15:52.780
Wells comes to meet Rolles as the story ends.

15:53.740 --> 16:03.720
Our central character is about to relate to H.G. Wells the horrific events that have gone on down on the farm.

16:04.920 --> 16:14.500
And in those events are really the germs for all of Wells' science fiction.

16:15.440 --> 16:30.200
I mean, you know, there's, there's a kind of a, a joke on H.G. Wells there. I mean we all owe a great debt to H.G. Wells because he preempted almost all of the science fiction themes.

16:31.040 --> 16:39.480
And so in a way the saliva tree is a kind of horrific joke to show that in fact Wells didn't have any original ideas.

16:39.480 --> 16:44.400
They were all given to him by this guy who knocks on the door at the end of the story.

16:45.640 --> 16:47.960
More on the works of Brian Aldiss next time.

