18:29.780 --> 18:34.560
English science fiction author Brian Aldiss sometimes writes books which are difficult to categorize.

18:34.560 --> 18:41.480
Aldiss has written familiar science fiction such as his first novel which was published in this country in 1959 as Starship.

18:41.480 --> 18:45.340
But many of his novels are experimental or avant-garde in both theme and structure.

18:45.340 --> 18:49.560
Report on Probability A, published in 1969 is a good example of this type.

18:49.560 --> 18:59.100
A 1976 novel though, The Malacia Tapestry, is one of his most unique novels, a strange but richly rewarding book, and it completely resists categories.

18:59.100 --> 19:04.520
It could be called science Fiction, but it's not quite that. Some might say it's fantasy, but it's not that either

19:04.520 --> 19:07.440
Aldiss talks about the inspiration behind the book.

19:08.460 --> 19:15.240
The model I had was a pictorial one that's often the case

19:16.840 --> 19:24.040
Well in several of my novels, I start from a pictorial beginning,

19:24.040 --> 19:38.720
and my pictorial beginnings with Malacia were the etchings which the Italian artist, the Baroque artist GBT Epilo, made at the end of his life

19:38.720 --> 19:47.100
Towards the end of his life, he retired and he started etching

19:47.100 --> 20:10.340
these mysterious little pictures of wizards, mountebanks, soldiers, punchinellos, people being dug out of the ground from graves, owls, serpents burning on altars,

20:10.340 --> 20:17.240
All sorts of mysterious symbols in these lovely little pictures, and no one's actually figured out what they're meant to be.

20:17.240 --> 20:26.440
It's like a science fictional alternative world where magic rules, I suppose you'd say.

20:27.360 --> 20:30.440
And I suppose that was one of the things I liked about them.

20:31.340 --> 20:39.940
So I thought, well if no one else can reconstruct this world to their satisfaction, I'll have a go at it.

20:41.160 --> 20:49.760
And so I started writing short stories around the more haunting of these etchings of Tiepolo's.

20:50.860 --> 20:57.020
Malacia itself is a grand city which exists in what appears to be an alternate universe suggestive of Earth's ancient past

20:57.020 --> 21:01.100
There is no technology to speak of, sorcery of a limited sort seems to work.

21:01.100 --> 21:05.280
And there are all manner of exotic creatures such as flying beings which resemble humans.

21:05.280 --> 21:12.480
The novel's main concern is art, an unusual theme for a science fiction or fantasy book, seemingly more appropriate for a romantic poet.

21:12.480 --> 21:17.120
Aldiss told us that the theme of art came out of a serious illness he had while writing the book.

21:17.120 --> 21:34.780
The effect of this internal complaint I had this hepatitis made me feel that, well my life span was limited and I had frolicked about a good deal.

21:34.780 --> 21:39.220
And had written some books that I perhaps didn't take as seriously as I should do.

21:40.520 --> 21:47.240
And that what I dearly loved was writing and that I wanted to make a statement about art.

21:49.300 --> 21:54.480
And really Malacia is, it's all about art from the title onwards.

21:54.480 --> 22:12.500
If the book has a power, it is the power of meditations on the nature of art which is at once to transfigure and at the same time to petrify

22:12.500 --> 22:25.600
And as you know Malacia itself is a city-state under a curse of zero change. Well that's like a work of art.

22:25.600 --> 22:34.220
It's like Tiepolo's little etchings. They may be forever enigmatic to us, but they're forever unchanging.

22:35.000 --> 22:42.140
The Malacia Tapestry, by one of the masters of modern science fiction, a difficult novel to categorize but a fascinating one to read.

22:42.140 --> 22:44.760
