24:26.020 --> 24:32.560
Brian Aldiss' latest science Fiction novel is the masterful achievement of an author who is at the height of his very awesome powers.

24:32.560 --> 24:40.920
It's called Helliconia Spring, and it's the first volume of a trilogy about an Earth-like planet called Helliconia. Aldiss tells us about the planet and the books.

24:42.460 --> 24:50.560
Helliconia is the name of a planet that's really much like Earth and a lot of Earth-like things go on there, but it is the child of binary suns,

24:58.340 --> 25:08.760
And it takes two and a half thousand years to go round the primary. I mean two and a half thousand Earth years,

25:11.500 --> 25:23.720
Which is to say that between one winter and the next, you can have a whole lot of civilizations doing a whole lot of declining and falling,

25:24.740 --> 25:27.860
and of course falling and rising.

25:28.680 --> 25:38.880
And so that these three long volumes really just cover parts of one of Helliconia's great years.

25:39.880 --> 25:52.180
So there's at once this marvelous continuity as I see it of one year and yet of many generations and many cultures.

25:53.980 --> 25:56.640
And that's the basic plan of the book.

25:56.640 --> 26:01.480
They're simply titled. The first one is Helliconia Spring. That's the one that's out.

26:01.480 --> 26:08.560
The one I'm writing is Helliconia Summer and after that I go on to Helliconia Winter.

26:09.680 --> 26:21.620
After centuries of a deadening winter, spring is coming to Helliconia and the primitive men of the planet are waking up to the greater possibilities of life, to higher aspirations and knowledge, to the construction of a new civilization

26:21.620 --> 26:26.720
The first volume traces the life of a nomadic hunter named Yuli and his descendants.

26:27.440 --> 26:30.820
Because the first volume is about the sun bursting out.

26:32.120 --> 26:43.580
The first volume is just stacked full of things bursting out, and people bursting out, animals bursting out. It's a great bursting out novel.

26:51.380 --> 26:58.700
Circling Helliconia is a satellite from Earth, a huge observation station which monitors everything that happens in Helliconia and beams it to Earth.

26:58.700 --> 27:03.840
Aldiss spent a painstaking four years on the book striving for accuracy and realism.

27:05.140 --> 27:09.820
Well I hope people will find that it's full of reality.

27:10.560 --> 27:19.940
That's why I say the moral of it should be mere existence. Because I think they recognize their own lives passing through the book.

27:20.920 --> 27:43.080
And the other motive I had was that I grew rather alarmed at the way so much science fiction since it's become more popular has been full of what shall we say fantasy wish fulfillment.

27:43.080 --> 27:45.220
I didn't like that.

27:45.220 --> 27:55.860
I think that science fiction should reflect the facts of life, the hard facts of life.

27:55.860 --> 28:11.980
It shouldn't just be some nonsense about one guy against a malign empire who goes out and you know kills the chief baddie. I thought it should have a little more contact for reality.

28:11.980 --> 28:27.680
And moreover I'll sound old fashioned if I say this, but I think that sort of thing is better for the nation's youth than the old hogwash about telepathic dragons and all the rest of it.

28:34.760 --> 28:41.760
Helliconia Spring is a remarkable and unique achievement by a man who is not just a great science fiction writer but one of the finest writers of our time.

